Citations
Date:  0/0/1941
Source:  NZ Slang
Author:  BAKER
Vol / Page:  50
Edition:
Quote:  Need to find some outlet for pent-up feelings resulted in the concoction of <i>blimey charley!</i> (why charley?); <i>by Christchurch. </i>
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1949
Source:  Dictionary of Slang Addenda
Author:  PARTRIDGE
Vol / Page:  992
Edition:
Quote:  <i>Blimey Charley!</i> A c.p. used to blow off pent-up emotions: New Zealand and Australian: 20C. B1941. In Australian, also <i>blimey Teddy! </i>
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1966
Source:  English Language in Aust. & NZ, The
Author:  TURNER
Vol / Page:  177
Edition:
Quote:  Some expressions that have been claimed for New Zealand are <i>at the rate of knots</i> `very fast', <i>hook your mutton</i> `clear out', <i>have the wood on</i> `have an advantage over' and the oaths <i>Blimey Charlie</i> and<i> (By) Christchurch </i>(obviously a neat save suggested by the place name).
Notes:

Date:  0/0/1988
Source:  Dictionary of Kiwi Slang, A
Author:  McGILL
Vol / Page:  15
Edition:
Quote:  <i>blimey, Charlie! </i>indicating friendly relief; obs.; derived from mostly Cockney `blimey' abbreviation of `Gorblimey', abbreviation of `God blind me'. NZA.
